* 2 _The comprehensive README generated using Prompt 1_


@code markdown

# Task Manager

A lightweight, extensible, and maintainable command-line task management application built with Node.js.

Task Manager follows a layered architecture with separate modules for:

* Task data modeling
* Business logic and task management
* Persistent storage
* Command-line interaction
* Task parsing and prioritization utilities
* Task synchronization and conflict resolution

The project is designed to provide a clean developer experience while remaining flexible enough for future expansion.

---

# Features

## Core Task Management

* Create and manage tasks
* Update task statuses
* Assign task priorities
* Add due dates
* Add and remove tags
* Delete tasks

## Task Organization

* Filter tasks by status
* Filter tasks by priority
* View overdue tasks
* View task details

## Persistence

* Automatically save tasks to disk
* Restore tasks from JSON storage

## Statistics & Analytics

* Total task counts
* Tasks grouped by status
* Tasks grouped by priority
* Overdue task tracking
* Recently completed tasks

## Advanced Utilities

* Parse free-form task input
* Rank tasks by importance
* Synchronize task lists
* Automatic conflict resolution

---

# Technologies Used

* Node.js
* Commander
* UUID
* Jest

---

# Installation

## Prerequisites

Make sure you have the following installed:

* Node.js (v14 or later recommended)
* npm

Verify installation:

```bash
node -v
npm -v
```

---

## Clone the Repository

```bash
git clone https://github.com/your-username/task-manager.git
cd task-manager
```

---

## Install Dependencies

```bash
npm install
```

This will install all required packages including:

* commander
* uuid
* jest

---

# Project Structure

```text
task-manager/
│
├── app.js                 # Core business logic
├── cli.js                 # Command-line interface
├── models.js              # Task models and enums
├── storage.js             # Persistent JSON storage
├── task_parse.js          # Free-form task parsing
├── task_priority.js       # Task scoring and ranking
├── task_list_merge.js     # Task synchronization utilities
├── tasks.json             # Persistent task storage
├── package.json
└── README.md
```

---

# Usage

## Run the CLI

```bash
node cli.js
```

To view help:

```bash
node cli.js --help
```

---

# Commands

## Create a Task

```bash
node cli.js create "Finish documentation"
```

With additional options:

```bash
node cli.js create "Finish report" \
  --description "Prepare final project report" \
  --priority 4 \
  --due 2026-06-01 \
  --tags work,urgent
```

### Priority Levels

| Value | Priority |
| ----- | -------- |
| 1     | Low      |
| 2     | Medium   |
| 3     | High     |
| 4     | Urgent   |

---

## List Tasks

List all tasks:

```bash
node cli.js list
```

Filter by status:

```bash
node cli.js list --status todo
```

Filter by priority:

```bash
node cli.js list --priority 4
```

Show overdue tasks:

```bash
node cli.js list --overdue
```

---

## Update Task Status

```bash
node cli.js status <task_id> done
```

Available statuses:

* todo
* in_progress
* review
* done

Example:

```bash
node cli.js status 123abc done
```

---

## Update Task Priority

```bash
node cli.js priority <task_id> 3
```

Example:

```bash
node cli.js priority 123abc 4
```

---

## Update Due Date

```bash
node cli.js due <task_id> 2026-06-10
```

---

## Add a Tag

```bash
node cli.js tag <task_id> backend
```

---

## Remove a Tag

```bash
node cli.js untag <task_id> backend
```

---

## Show Task Details

```bash
node cli.js show <task_id>
```

---

## Delete a Task

```bash
node cli.js delete <task_id>
```

---

## View Statistics

```bash
node cli.js stats
```

Example output:

```text
Total tasks: 12

By status:
  todo: 5
  in_progress: 3
  review: 2
  done: 2

By priority:
  1: 1
  2: 4
  3: 5
  4: 2

Overdue tasks: 3
Completed in last 7 days: 2
```

---

# Free-Form Task Parsing

The project includes utilities for parsing natural-language task input.

## Supported Syntax

| Syntax        | Meaning              |
| ------------- | -------------------- |
| `@tag`        | Add a tag            |
| `!1-4`        | Set numeric priority |
| `!high`       | Set named priority   |
| `#today`      | Set due date         |
| `#tomorrow`   | Due tomorrow         |
| `#friday`     | Due next Friday      |
| `#YYYY-MM-DD` | Explicit due date    |

## Example

```text
Finish report !urgent @work #tomorrow
```

Parsed as:

* Title: Finish report
* Priority: Urgent
* Tag: work
* Due Date: Tomorrow

---

# Task Prioritization Engine

The task prioritization utility calculates a dynamic importance score based on:

* Task priority
* Due dates
* Overdue status
* Tags
* Task status
* Recent updates

This helps identify the most important tasks automatically.

---

# Task Synchronization

The synchronization module merges task lists from local and remote sources.

## Conflict Resolution Rules

* Most recently updated task wins
* Completed tasks override incomplete versions
* Tags are merged automatically
* Status conflicts are resolved intelligently

The merge utility returns:

* Tasks to create remotely
* Tasks to update remotely
* Tasks to create locally
* Tasks to update locally

---

# Configuration

## Storage File

By default, tasks are stored in:

```text
tasks.json
```

You can customize the storage path when creating a `TaskManager` instance:

```js
const manager = new TaskManager('custom_tasks.json');
```

---

# Development

## Run Tests

```bash
npm test
```

---

## Install Jest

If Jest is not already installed:

```bash
npm install --save-dev jest
```

---

# Troubleshooting

## Invalid Date Format

Problem:

```text
Invalid date format. Use YYYY-MM-DD
```

Solution:

Ensure dates use this format:

```text
2026-05-28
```

---

## Tasks Not Persisting

Possible causes:

* Missing write permissions
* Corrupted `tasks.json`
* Invalid JSON format

Try deleting `tasks.json` and rerunning the application.

---

## Module Not Found Errors

Run:

```bash
npm install
```

to reinstall dependencies.

---

## UUID Errors

Ensure the `uuid` package is installed:

```bash
npm install uuid
```

---

# Contributing

Contributions are welcome.

## Steps

1. Fork the repository
2. Create a feature branch

```bash
git checkout -b feature/my-feature
```

3. Commit your changes

```bash
git commit -m "Add new feature"
```

4. Push to your branch

```bash
git push origin feature/my-feature
```

5. Open a pull request

---

# Future Improvements

Potential enhancements include:

* SQLite or database support
* REST API integration
* Web dashboard
* Authentication
* Notifications/reminders
* Recurring tasks
* Cloud synchronization
* Task dependencies
* Search functionality

